Out of the total sampled population, ninety-one weavers (16%) were infected during summer sampling months and 59 weavers (10%) were infected during winter sampling. Overall infection prevalence displayed significant seasonal variation (Figure  
   1; 
   x
   2 = 180; d. f. = 81; 
   p < 0.001). Southern Red Bishops were the most abundant weaver species caught and also were the most heavily infected weaver species, with 26% of caught birds infected (Figure  
   2). Southern Red Bishops were also the only species to display significant variation in infection prevalence between seasons (
   x
   
    2
    = 21.86; 
   p < 0.001), with most birds infected during the summer.

Plasmodium prevalence was best described by seasonal factors (with winter as the significant season); mosquito prevalence; salinity; and rainfall at a lag of 4 months (Table  
4). Rainfall during the sampling month was also a relevant factor, although not as influential. Significant reductions in the goodness of fit of the best model occurred when any explanatory variables were omitted. Season caused the greatest reduction when omitted (likelihood ratio = 17.47; 
p < 0.001) and rainfall (at four months) the least reduction (likelihood ratio = 4.16; 
p = 0.04).
